How Travel Prices have evolved since 1989
By 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at this time offered trips mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crime and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a link to the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited to Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist block (also for the Czechoslovakian people) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the case where the citizens of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or in the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, but the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at this time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to cook all night with a shower or to have a "good knowledge" inside the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for loans that were the condition for travel to the west was rejected by the "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
