The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the United Nations (SCJN) has raised constitutional disputes that the Senate and the Chamber of Members have formulated against the presidential decree, which goes on to say "analogous cover" from 2021 to 2015, since the eight votes required for invalidation were not met.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his duties when he issued the decree detailing the steps to be taken to establish the transition to terrestrial digital television.
As a result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic has been resolved not to reach the qualified majority of eight votes in order for the Court to speak on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree to continue to be in force.
The draft judgment, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because radio and television regulation is a duty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), contrary to the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Members have promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the order and, by adopting complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the order and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The Plenary Meeting of Ministers also decided to draw up the complaint made by the House of Members, without discussing the draft which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his intervention, the Prime Minister said that he was not in agreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive could not structure the measures for the public administration to prepare them through general standards.
"I no longer consider that it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional authority of the State.
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and this is the result of a better operation of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels.
To update the change, he supported, would update the benefits of digitization, which involves a decision of public interest which is not only a technical dimension, "which also includes national economic, social, political and security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "requires the operation of any established system, in accordance with the principle of state economic management, to include a group of tasks granted by the Constitution to the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, although they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested order, has in one way taken over the sphere of Congress's competence, as it ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws issued by the Act.
