Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in areas where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and consequently the formation of cases.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a combination of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called Malteses, which together give the pope its viscosity.
The viscosity of the asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes falling, adding it.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in most of them were covered by a flexible floor consisting of six layers of materials, the last three involving the asphalt.
Among the most surface layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stone cut into asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones forming the layer, it signaled, is washed in asphalt.
When vehicles make efforts there, it allows the forces to thrive very well in the deck.
If we had changed the asphalt, they would have spread better, considering the chemical engineering.
On the asphalt layer, he said, it was put on a last layer called a rolling layer, made in fine stone, that is, of the sand that is also washed in asphalt.
